  "prompt": "What aspect of studying at Oxford has surprised you the most?",
  "response": "I don't have personal experiences or feelings, but I can provide some insights based on common feedback from students who have studied at Oxford. One aspect that often surprises students is the tutorial system. This unique approach involves regular, intensive discussions with an expert tutor, usually in very small groups or one-on-one, which can be quite different from the lecture-based learning many students are accustomed to. The depth of intellectual engagement and personalized feedback can be both challenging and rewarding.\n\nAdditionally, the collegiate system might surprise students at Oxford. Each student belongs to a college, which serves as their home base for social and academic activities. This can foster a strong sense of community and belonging, but it also means that some facilities and resources are divided among colleges rather than centralized.\n\nLastly, students might be surprised by the rich tradition and history embedded in daily life at Oxford, from formal dinners and centuries-old rituals to the architecture and libraries. This can create a unique atmosphere that blends academic rigor with historical grandeur.",
